Is there a black box in your car?
While American road designers are trying to find money to repair the crumbling highway system, many begin to see the solution in a small black box neatly attached to the dashboard of your car.
These devices, which track every mile traveled by a motorist and transmit this information to officials, are at the heart of a controversial attempt to modernize America’s outdated highway financing system undertaken by the planning authorities of Washington and the state.
The usually boring arena of motorway planning has unexpectedly spawned intense debates and colorful alliances.
Libertarians have joined environmental groups in lobbying to give the government the right to use small boxes to track the number of miles you’ve driven and perhaps even where you’ve driven them — and then use that information when compiling tax bills.
The tea party is in shock.
The American Civil Liberties Union is also deeply concerned and raises a number of privacy issues.
And while Congress can’t agree on whether to continue or not, several states aren’t going to wait.
They are reflecting on how over the next decade we can move to a system where drivers pay for every mile of the road they drive.
Thousands of motorists have already taken to testing these black boxes, some of which have a satellite tracking function.
This is really necessary for our country.
“It’s not an issue we have the right to choose on,” said Hasan Ichrata, executive director of the Southern California Government Association, which is making plans to start tracking the miles driven by every Californian motorist by 2025.
There will be changes in how we pay these taxes.
The technology for this already exists.
The need for this is compounded by the lack of funds from the Government Highway Construction Fund, financed by taxes that Americans pay at gas stations.
Americans don’t buy as much gasoline as they used to.
Cars travel more miles per gallon.
The federal tax, 18.4 cents per gallon, has not been raised in 20 years.
Politicians do not want to raise the tax even by one cent at high gasoline prices.
“The gasoline tax is simply impossible to keep,” said Lee Mannich, a transport policy expert at the University of Minnesota.
In his state, 500 tracking devices were recently installed on cars to test the system of erroneous payment.
“This will be the best alternative in the long run,” he said.
The boredom calls it a false user board.
It is not surprising that this idea attracts urban liberals, since with the help of taxes it will be possible to change the nature of travel to reduce road congestion and greenhouse gas emissions, for example.
Planners in California are keeping an eye on the system as they develop strategies to meet the targets set by the state’s ambitious global warming laws.
However, House Speaker Bill Schuster (Republican, Pennsylvania), chairman of the House Transport Committee, said he, too, sees the system as the most viable long-term alternative.
Adherents of the free market in the fund “Reason” are also delighted that they will make drivers pay for every mile.
“It’s not just a tax that goes into a black hole,” said Adrian Moore, Reason’s vice president of political affairs.
People pay directly for what they get.
The movement is also backed by two former U.S. transport ministers who in 2011 called on Congress to move towards mispayment.
Last year, the U.S. Senate approved a $90 million pilot project that would involve about 10,000 vehicles.
However, House leaders rejected the proposal because of concerns from rural lawmakers representing voters who often have to travel many miles in everyday life to get to work or to the city.
Several states and cities, however, are going this route on their own.
The greatest enthusiasm is shown in Oregon, where 5,000 drivers are attracted to participate in the country’s largest experiment.
These drivers will soon pay the state mileage instead of a gasoline tax.
In Nevada, the pilot project has already been completed.
It is being considered in New York.
Illinois will test it on a limited basis with trucks.
And the I-95 coalition, which includes the transport departments of 17 East Coast states (including Maryland, Pennsylvania, Virginia and Florida), is exploring how they can implement these changes.
This concept has not been universally accepted.
In Nevada, where about 50 volunteer cars were recently fitted with these devices, drivers were concerned that the government could track their every move.
“Concern about Big Brother and things like that is a big deal,” said Alauddin Khan, head of strategy and performance management at the Nevada Department of Transportation.
It wasn’t what people wanted.
When the tests were underway, the American Civil Liberties Union's Nevada office warned on its website: "It will not be difficult to turn these devices into full-scale surveillance devices."
There is no need to create a huge, cumbersome technological infrastructure, which will inevitably be expanded to store records of the daily movements of individual citizens.
Nevada is one of a handful of states that are struggling to find an inexpensive technology that would allow state authorities to keep track of miles traveled by car, but without the information about the place and time.
If you can do that, Khan said, society would feel more at ease.
The search for this technology led some state agencies to a small young company in California called True Mileage.
Initially, this company was not engaged in assistance in collecting state taxes.
It sought to enter the emerging market of a type of auto insurance in which drivers pay on the basis of mileage.
But the devices it tests attract road designers because they don’t use GPS and provide a limited amount of information downloaded periodically via a modem.
“People will be more likely to do this if you don’t track their speed and track their location,” said Ryan Morrison, executive director of True Mileage.
There have been some big mistakes in some of these state pilot programs.
There are much less expensive and less intrusive ways to do this.
In Oregon, designers are experimenting with giving drivers a variety of options.
They can choose a device with or without GPS.
Or they can give up the device altogether, deciding instead to pay a flat fee based on the average number of miles all state residents drive.
Elsewhere, they hope to sell the idea to a wary public, forcing devices to do more, not less.
In New York, transport officials are looking to develop a taxable device that will also accept parking meter payments, provide “pay as you drive” insurance, and collect a real-time speed data pool from other drivers that motorists could use to avoid traffic jams.
“Automobilists will be attracted to participate in the benefits that will be offered to them,” – said in the document of urban planning.
Some transport system designers, however, wonder if all the talk of mispayment is just a huge distraction.
At the San Francisco Bay Area City Transportation Commission, officials say Congress could very easily overcome the bankruptcy of the trusted Highway Construction Fund by raising taxes on gasoline.
An additional one-off or annual tax could be levied on drivers of hybrid cars and other individuals whose vehicles do not use much gasoline so that they pay their fair share.
“There’s no need for radical surgery when all you have to do is take an aspirin,” said Randy Rentschler, director of the Legislation and Public Relations Commission.
If we do this, hundreds of millions of drivers will be worried about their privacy and a host of other things.
EU prepares measures to support Ukraine in case of economic pressure from Russia
The European Union has a contingency plan to provide Ukraine with gas, as well as to reach an agreement with the IMF on an emergency loan if Russia takes any action in response to the possible signing of an association agreement between the EU and Ukraine at the Vilnius summit.
Negotiations are underway with the IMF on a stand-by loan, and another EU official directly involved in the negotiations added that their goal is to conclude an agreement in the near future.
At the same time, in addition to a potential loan from the IMF, Ukraine can receive 610 million euros from the European Union itself.
Analysts interviewed by Reuters doubt that Ukraine and the IMF are able to overcome long-standing disagreements about the terms of funding.
He does not believe in the possibility of reforms necessary to get help, and the international rating agency S&P, which on Friday lowered the sovereign rating of Ukraine by one step - to "B-" from "B".
However, EU officials say that the IMF can show flexibility in lending conditions, taking into account the circumstances of Ukraine.
In addition to the country’s financial support plan, the EU has a standby option to provide Ukraine with gas, the vast majority of which now comes from Russia.
Perhaps it will be gas from Nord Stream or reverse from Slovakia.
The latter, according to officials, is the most possible and acceptable way in case Russia “isolates” Ukraine.
Analysts believe that this method of reversing deliveries to Ukraine can be used only for a few weeks, and is likely to lead to a decrease in deliveries to other regions.
"There are talks between EU countries and Ukrainians on how to create favorable conditions so that Ukraine can import gas from other sources than Russia or from the same source, but on different routes," the source added.
Russia out of the fight to pollute cities with cars
Attempts to solve the transport problems of large cities have been observed in most metropolitan areas of the world since the second half of the twentieth century.
As a rule, it was either about their reconstruction and expansion of highways, or about attempts to reduce the demand for road trips, the number of cars and the time of their use.
Singapore is a well-known example, where there is a strict quota for the growth of private cars, and the right to purchase them is bought at auctions.
Its price can be two to three times higher than the price of the car itself.
European cities, including London, have introduced entry fees to the city centre.
In Germany, for example, in Hamburg and Stuttgart, so-called green zones are introduced, where only cars with a certain eco-class are allowed to enter, also using high-quality fuels (including biofuels or electric cars).
Beijing’s Environmental Protection Agency, for example, approved a “five-year clean air plan” in 2012 worth about 250 billion yuan (about $40 billion).
According to Li Kunsheng, director of the Department of Transport Pollution Control of the Beijing Municipal Environmental Protection Bureau, the main goal of the five-year plan is to reduce the leading air pollutants by 20-35% by 2017, increase the number of private cars to the level of no more than 6 million (currently 5.2 million), as well as increase fuel consumption by no more than 5% per vehicle.
According to the agency, now vehicles in Beijing are responsible for 22.5% of total air pollution.
Among the main measures of the program are the restriction of the use of road transport, as well as the introduction of additional taxes for car owners.
Among other things, the urban measures of the "green five-year plan" include accelerated in comparison with the rest of the country the transition to European fuel standards, the introduction of a local system of eco-standards and the labeling of cars and fuel, the restriction on the entry of cars in the central part of the city, the prohibition on the use of obsolete vehicles (in addition, the creation of incentives for electric vehicles).
Beijing's automotive innovations also include a ban on all private cars to move within the fifth transport ring (total of six in the capital of the People's Republic of China) one day a week (the relevant information is contained in the vehicle license plate), as well as the issuance of registration plates for cars based on the lottery (for example, in 2011, the first year of the Beijing lottery, the third part of the year, the total number of permits for the lottery).
According to the current state program “Environmental protection for 2012-2020”, the number of cities with high and very high air pollution should be reduced to 128 (in 2012 there were 138).
According to the Ministry of Natural Resources, in 2011 “mobile sources” accounted for 41% of all pollutant emissions into the atmosphere of cities.
In Moscow, for example, emissions from cars are ten times higher than industrial, and in St. Petersburg - nine times.
In the Russian Federation, they are just beginning to think about the possibilities of restrictive regulation of cars on the streets of cities.
The Director of the Institute of Transport Economics and Transport Policy of HSE Mikhail Blinkin believes that administrative and fiscal measures aimed at suppressing the demand for road trips are obviously unpopular, they can be taken by society only under the condition of their complete universality.
In the case of Moscow, there is a unique problem associated with the structure of its fleet, where there are two clusters weakly sensitive to any regulatory influences - service and personal cars, as well as cars of "privileged" users, the total number of which is not less than 200 thousand (about 5% of the total number of the fleet of Moscow).
Recently, urbanists from the ECOM center in St. Petersburg prepared a study that analyzes the balance of urban areas between residential development, road surface area and the number of vehicles.
The main findings of the researchers: the city center is provided with roads twice less than required, and most motorists living in the center do not use cars every day, leaving them for a long time in parking lots or just on the streets.
As a result, it is proposed to build not parking lots, but car storage, not to expand, but to reduce the roadway (so that the streets become more pedestrian-friendly), as well as to limit the use and placement of personal transport within the territory of the protected zone of the historical center (a total area of about 3,212 hectares, covering a number of central districts of the city).
Fines for unauthorized street trade in Vologda will increase by several times
According to the city authorities, the increase in fines will help to restore order in Vologda and free the streets from elementary tents and trays.
Most street vendors do not pay taxes, and the products they sell often do not pass appropriate sanitation controls.
And this means that the health of Vologjans is at risk.
Thus, the lower limit of the fine for citizens for unauthorized trade from November will increase six times - from 500 rubles to 3000 rubles, the press service of the Vologda Administration reports.
Goldman Sachs warns of risks to Russian economy
Goldman Sachs has warned of growing risks to Russia’s main driver of fragile economic growth – consumption.
This is primarily a crisis of non-payment of unsecured consumer loans and mass reductions of workers.
Our main concern now is not that growth has slowed down, but rather the structure of that growth.
Recently, it is entirely driven by consumption, which almost does not slow down the turnover," said Clemens Grafe, Goldman Sachs chief economist for Russia, presenting the quarterly report of the investment bank on the Russian economy.
Now the nominal growth of wages in Russia is about 10%.
With inflation at 6%, it will be able to meet future consumer demand at about the current level, Goldman Sachs expects.
But the profitability of Russian companies is declining, so it is likely that they will be engaged in optimizing personnel costs.
Today, we see a significant increase in the share of wages in GDP: if wages grow by 10%, then GDP - only by 2%, - explained Mr. Grafe.
Companies are facing a decline in profitability.
If it does not grow, it can lead to layoffs and an increase in unemployment.
Russian business cannot not raise wages, comments the chief economist of Barclays Capital for Russia and the CIS Vladimir Pantiushin.
Unemployment near historical lows, competition for workers is high.
In order to attract employees from the outside or keep current ones, employers have to raise wages.
Consumption in Russia is supported by the very rapid growth of consumer lending.
According to Mr. Grafe, due to the extremely high rates on consumer loans, this type of lending does not have a multiplicative effect on the economy of the country.
“We have not seen any benefits for the economy from the growth of demand, money does not diverge across the economy, but returns to the same banks in the form of interest payments,” the economist said.
But the problem is another - Goldman Sachs expects an increase in arrears on unsecured loans.
They are mostly taken by poor people who have nothing to provide.
Interest on such loans is high.
As a result, they are not returned more often," said Mr. Grafe.
Therefore, the second threat to the growth of the economy in Russia is a possible crisis of non-payment of unsecured loans.
The director of the HSE Banking Institute, Vasily Solodkov, is already seeing signs of an impending banking crisis.
Small credit institutions, not having access to cheap resources, such as state banks, were forced to attract funds of the population at high interest rates.
In response, the state banks went on the path of war and began to reduce credit rates, - continues the economist.
Small credit institutions cannot lend at the same interest rate, otherwise they will have a negative interest margin.
If the state banks do not abandon dumping, Russia is threatened with a full-fledged banking crisis, believes Vasily Solodkov.
The deprivation of licenses of a number of banks in recent weeks, the economist considers a forerunner of a mass collapse.
“The state banks themselves will not cope with this situation: the deposit insurance system was initially not designed for a systemic crisis,” the head of the institute warns.
But the growth of consumption will slow down without a crisis of non-payments, the investment bank believes, due to the refusal to index the salaries of civil servants and military, laid down in the current version of the draft budget.
Part of the impact on consumption will be mitigated by freezing the tariffs of natural monopolies (and, consequently, reducing inflation).
But only partially: if investment does not grow (and there are no prerequisites for this - see the help), the growth of consumption will still slow down, according to Goldman Sachs.
Vladimir Pantyushin of Barclays Capital does not yet see the prerequisites for the implementation of pessimistic scenarios.
“The main risk is still the fall in oil prices,” he says.
According to him, the Russian economy will begin to shrink at the cost of oil below $ 90 / barrel.
Goldman Sachs also noted that the Central Bank is not yet able to lower interest rates in the economy.
There is a paradoxical picture: inflation decreased, and banks began to raise rates.
This may mean that they did not believe the Central Bank, which announced the transition to inflation targeting,” said Clemens Grafe.
The central bank’s interest rate policy does not affect market rates, it only affects interbank lending rates.
“For the Central Bank, this is the collapse of all hopes,” said Clemens Grafe.
The money received at the auctions of the Central Bank, banks use not for lending to the economy, but to manage their liquidity
As soon as the rate decreases, the exchange rate immediately changes, which means that the funds are trying to go on speculation against the ruble.
"Sooner or later, the Central Bank will realize that this strategy does not work," Grafe said, recalling that the state plans to release the ruble into "free navigation" by the end of 2015.
But you will have to either do it earlier or raise the key rate of the Central Bank (5.5%), he believes.
According to him, the ruble is now artificially overvalued by 10%.
I cut only one way - to weaken, - the expert concludes.
But if the Central Bank plunges into the financiers even a shadow of a doubt that the liquidation of the currency corridor is not part of the policy to weaken the ruble, it can bring down the ruble much stronger.
