Snowden ready to ‘cooperate’ with Germany on U.S. intelligence
Edward Snowden, a U.S. intelligence whistleblower, said he was prepared to go to Berlin to testify to the German parliament if the U.S. National Security Agency and its director, Keith Alexander, were unable to answer questions about their activities.
German MP Hans-Christian Ströbele met with Mr Snowden in Russia on Thursday, where he was granted asylum to discuss his testimony in Germany.
A letter from Mr. Snowden, which the MP presented to the media in Berlin on Friday, said: “Although the result of my efforts has been clearly positive, my government continues to treat dissent as treason and seeks to criminalize political statements with criminal charges that offer no defense whatsoever.”
But telling the truth is not a crime.
In the letter, Snowden said he believes the support of the international community can convince the U.S. government to drop criminal charges against him.
The charges brought by the U.S. Department of Justice include espionage and theft of state property.
Hans-Peter Friedrich, Germany’s interior minister, told Zeit Online: “If Mr. Snowden is willing to talk to German officials, we will find ways to make it possible.”
Relations between the United States and Germany have become tense after allegations that the NSA was tapping Chancellor Angela Merkel’s phone.
Thomas Opperman, a lawmaker who heads a parliamentary group overseeing the intelligence service, said if there is an opportunity to hear Mr Snowden as a witness, “without endangering him and destroying relations with the United States completely,” it should be used.
Mr. Ströbele, a member of parliament for the German Green Party, posted a photo of himself with Mr. Snowden on his Twitter account.
During his visit to Russia, he was accompanied by two German journalists.
Mr. Ströbele said that, according to the lawyer of the former NSA contractor, Mr. Snowden would not have been able to return to Russia if he had left.
If Mr. Snowden were to testify in Germany, he would need guarantees that he would be there “safe,” the MP said.
Mr. Snowden said in his letter that he faced a “hard and constant” persecution campaign that forced him to leave his home.
However, he said he was encouraged by the world's reaction to "his political remarks."
Citizens around the world, as well as senior officials — including in the United States — have found exposing an uncontrolled system of all-encompassing surveillance useful to society.
The letter offers to cooperate with the German authorities “when the difficulties of this humanitarian situation are resolved”.
Frontier Airlines will charge a fee for hand luggage
Frontier Airlines plans to charge passengers up to $100 for carrying hand luggage on board their flight.
Frontier Airlines plans to start charging up to $100 for hand luggage and $2 for coffee or soda, though their announcement on Wednesday said passengers would be able to keep the entire bank.
The new hand luggage fee applies to bags in the upper luggage compartments, so small bags placed under the seat will remain free.
Frontier said it would charge $25 if the fee was paid in advance, and $100 if travelers would pay only at the gate.
Frontier spokeswoman Kate O’Malley said the $100 fee should make passengers take care of paying in advance.
“We don’t want to charge a fee for that,” she said.
Airlines began charging a fee for the first and second bags to be placed in luggage in 2008.
Passengers trying to avoid these charges stuff as much as they can into hand luggage placed in the upper luggage compartments, which is why these compartments often lack space.
Fees are one way to get passengers to carry less on board.
O'Malley said the new fee wasn't really about making money.
The fact is that Frontier’s most loyal customers claim that finding a place in the upper luggage compartments is becoming increasingly difficult.
Passengers who buy tickets on the airline’s website will not have to pay.
This means that one passenger in the queue at the front of a Frontier flight can get the opportunity to carry a bag for free, while the next passenger in the queue can pay $100 for the same bag.
O’Malley said the changes to the procedures on the Frontier website and check-in counters are designed to ensure that passengers are aware of the charge before they reach the gate.
The new Frontier Hand Baggage Fee will not start charging until the summer, although a date has not yet been set.
Passengers often complain about baggage and other fees, but airlines love them.
They argue that baggage handling costs money, and passengers who need this service must pay for it.
Many on Wall Street see the addition of baggage charges as a sign that airlines are charging enough money to cover air travel costs after years of losses.
However, most of them were not related to hand luggage fees.
Spirit Airlines Inc. introduced the first hand luggage fee three years ago, and another discounter, Allegiant Air, later followed suit.
The only other airline with such a fee is Hungarian Wizz Air, said airline consultant Jay Sorensen, who closely monitors the additional fees.
According to his December 2011 report, the hand luggage fee brings Spirit $50 million a year.
Sorensen, a former top manager of Midwest Airlines, recently flew a Spirit flight, and he was curious what he would find at the gate when passengers encountered an unusual Spirit baggage charge.
“The landing process was the smoothest I’ve seen in my airline career,” he said.
I expected to see the gnashing of teeth and the emergence of a fight at the landing gate.
The plane was full, he said, “and the landing was swift.”
Frontier also follows Spirit regarding a $2 fee for coffee, tea, soda or juice.
Frontier said passengers who receive soda or juice can keep the entire jar, and that coffee replenishment will be provided free of charge.
She will still be giving away water for free.
US Airways briefly tried to charge drinks in 2008, but declined seven months after passengers began complaining and no other major airline followed suit.
The Frontier initiative to charge hand luggage when passengers do not buy tickets directly from the airline is its latest measure to attract customers to its website.
Airlines pay online ticket vendors, such as Orbitz, between $10 and $25 for each ticket sold.
This has given all airlines an incentive to encourage passengers to buy tickets directly from them, rather than contact an online travel agency.
However, Frontier went further than anyone else in this area.
In September, it began giving twice as many frequent flyer bonus miles to customers who bought tickets through an online travel agency.
On Wednesday, she cut the miles bonus to 25 percent of the trip’s mileage.
For example, a 1,000-mile journey with Frontier, purchased from an online travel agency, would allow you to earn 250 miles.
In addition, passengers can choose a seat in advance only if they buy tickets directly on the Frontier website.
Frontier has a loyal customer base in its hometown of Denver, but its business is shrinking and becoming unprofitable.
Revenue fell 9 percent and flight capacity fell nearly 13 percent in the first quarter, according to financial results released Wednesday by parent company Republic Airways Holdings Inc.
The Republic is trying to fix Frontier's finances as part of the airline's sale.
NSA blames ‘internal error’, not hackers for website shutdown
The secretive National Security Agency said Friday night that the shutdown of their site for several hours caused a technical failure, not hackers, as the network claimed.
“NSA.gov was unavailable for several hours tonight due to an internal error that occurred during a scheduled update,” the intelligence agency said in an official email.
The problem will be solved tonight.
Claims that the outage was caused by a distributed denial-of-service (DDoS) attack are incorrect.
Earlier this evening, online server monitoring systems reported that the NSA site had been down for at least six hours and the site was still unavailable to some users.
Earlier, an NSA spokesman told ABC News that the agency’s internal secret network was “by no means” hacked.
No classified information is at risk, the official said.
At least one online group of activist hackers said it was responsible for disabling the NSA’s website through a DDoS attack.
DDoS attacks are designed to overwhelm the target site with traffic until the servers are overloaded and the site fails.
The tactics of hackers are relatively simple, and the attacks are not designed to penetrate the internal network of the target system.
Previously, the super-secret NSA, once nicknamed “No Such Agency,” has been in the center of public attention and fierce criticism in recent months after a series of revelations about its extensive surveillance programs abroad and at home – all in reaction to secret NSA files stolen from the agency and published by a disappointed former NSA employee.
The growing controversy surrounding the agency has sparked rumours that today’s incident was the result of targeted hackers’ actions.
Bombardier’s profits are declining with falling shipments and aircraft orders
Bombardier, a Canadian aircraft and train manufacturer, reported a 15 percent decline in net profit on Thursday, driven by declining orders and deliveries in the third quarter and contract issues at its rail division.
Montreal-based Bombardier has also not released any flight test data for its newest CSeries aircraft and has not provided any new information on whether ambitious plans to bring the aircraft into commercial operation by next September will be implemented.
After the first flight of the prototype aircraft, which took place about a month and a half ago, it flew only three more times, which raises questions about whether the testing stage is on schedule.
The results did not meet the forecasts and led to a fall in stocks by more than 8 percent on the Toronto Stock Exchange.
Cameron Doerksen, an analyst at National Bank Financial, lowered his rating on Thursday from “above the average market” to “average market” because of the belief that stock growth is limited in the next quarter or two.
“While the decline in aircraft deliveries was generally predictable, we are certainly disappointed with the transportation department’s profit margins,” Doerxen said in the stock market review.
We believe that Bombardier will receive new orders for the CSeries as the flight testing program continues.
However, if no new orders are announced in the coming months, we assume that the market will be more skeptical of the program.
Bombardier hopes that the CSeries family of aircraft will allow it to win a place in the lower price segment of the market, which is now dominated by Boeing and Airbus.
The first prototype of the aircraft was presented in March and first flew in September after several months of delay.
However, firm orders for the CSeries are not too much - 177, as potential buyers wait for the results of flight tests to test the company's claims about fuel efficiency and potential economy of the new liner.
In total, there are now 403 orders and agreements with 15 customers and operators.
Chief Executive Officer Pierre Baudouin was confident that Bombardier would reach its target of 300 firm orders by the time the first aircraft went into commercial operation.
On Thursday, leaders also assured analysts and the media that the program is moving ahead as planned.
“The test model of the aircraft did not stay on the ground longer than expected,” Baudouin said during a telephone conference, adding that ground tests and software updates were planned for the aircraft’s downtime.
All manufacturers plan testing differently.
We decided to take the first flight and take a break for updates, and we did.
This will be the case throughout the flight test program.
The second of the five test samples is due to fly in the coming weeks and all the others will follow soon, the company said.
Still, analysts are skeptical of the announcement that the first customer will be able to start operating the CSeries aircraft 12 months after its first flight.
Bombardier said it is assessing the commissioning period and will provide new information in the next few months.
“This slow pace of flight testing – although apparently consistent with Bombardier’s internal schedule – reinforces our view that commissioning will be postponed to the first quarter of 2015,” Doerxen said.
In the third quarter ended September 30, Bombardier’s net income fell to $147 million, or 8 cents per share, from $172 million, or 9 cents per share, last year.
Adjusted earnings per share remained the same - 9 cents.
Gross income fell slightly – from $4.2 to $4.1 billion.
Analysts expected earnings of 10 cents per share and gross revenue of $4.56 billion, according to Thomson Reuters I/B/E/S.
The world’s fourth-largest aircraft manufacturer said it delivered 45 aircraft in the quarter, down from 57 the previous year.
The total number of orders fell from 83 to 26 aircraft.
The portfolio of orders of the aerospace department amounted to $32.9 billion as of September 30, unchanged from December 31.
“In the aerospace field, the results were in line with our goals, but the small number of incoming orders and general market conditions have become an unpleasant factor,” Baudouin said.
Gross revenue in the aerospace sector fell by 13 percent to $2 billion.
Bombardier, the world’s largest train maker, said gross revenue in the sector grew nearly 11 percent to $2.1 billion.
The portfolio of orders in the transport division amounted to $32.6 billion as of September 30, which is slightly higher than on December 31.
The revenues of the transport unit were negatively affected by problems with the execution of several large contracts.
Management stated that a new development plan would be presented in the fourth quarter.
Shares of Bombardier, which also announced that Google’s chief financial officer Patrick Pichett would join the board, fell 8.5 percent to C$4.83 at auction in mid-Thursday.
Brazil’s Embraer SA, the world’s third-largest commercial aircraft manufacturer and Bombardier’s closest competitor, reported a 10 percent decline in quarterly revenue on Thursday.
Sony expects lower annual profits
Japanese electronics manufacturer Sony Corporation, having completed the last quarter with a net loss of 19.3 billion yen, or $197 million, cut the forecast of profit for the current fiscal year.
Sony’s results from July to September 2013 were more depressing than expected, driven by a drop in demand for the Japanese-made televisions, video cameras and personal computers.
Sony's TV business, which generated its first operating profit of 5.2 billion yen in three years in Q2, fell again to 9.3 billion yen of operating loss in the reporting period.
The Japanese consumer electronics market is going through tough times, especially due to declining demand for TVs.
