The speech gene was a stimulator of synapse formation
Scientists from Johns Hopkins University and Mount Sinai School of Medicine have discovered a protein through which the “speech gene” Foxp2 performs its function, stimulating the formation of new connections between neurons.
The study is published in Science, on the website of the journal you can read its summary.
The Foxp2 gene is the first known gene whose function is directly related to speech.
His role was established in 2001 thanks to the discovery of a family of several people who could not pronounce words correctly and sometimes did not even understand each other.
Scientists found that family members had impaired the work of the gene Foxp2, but how it performs its function, remained unknown.
In the new study, biologists have shown that at least part of its functions Foxp2 performs as a stimulator of the formation of new synapses in the brain area associated with the formation of speech.
This is done by another gene, SRPX2.
The latter was discovered as a result of the search for factors that stimulate the formation of synapses.
SRPX2 was one of 10 similar genes found by the authors, with only its activity shimmering Foxp2.
That SRPX2 really affects vocalization, the scientists confirmed in an experiment on mice.
When the animals’ gene activity was artificially reduced, they shouted less when separated from their mother.
If the activity of the gene was restored, the frequency of the emitted sounds was restored.
Previously, mice were also shown to be associated with the vocalization of Foxp2 itself.
Animals who were injected with a human copy of the gene whistled more actively and at a lower frequency than normal mice.
So far, however, scientists do not know whether the work of Foxp2 and, consequently, the SRPX2 controlled by it is related to purely "mechanical" properties of sound formation or more subtle processes.
