Within two weeks, there were almost daily reports of clashes between government forces and Renamo — some of the most violent clashes since the ceasefire was concluded more than 20 years ago.
Renamo was once a notorious rebel movement that was supported first by the white Rhodesian authorities and then by the apartheid-era South African government as part of an effort to destabilize the country’s independent government.
After the 1992 truce, it became an opposition party.
Analysts believe that the country is unlikely to slide back into a full-scale conflict, but recent events have made foreign investors and local residents nervous.
The stakes are high for a fast-growing economy, as the opening of huge offshore gas reserves and coal deposits in the northwest could attract more than $50 billion in investment over the next few years from companies such as Rio Tinto, Vale from Brazil, Eni from Italy and Anadarko from the US.
The ruling Frelimo party, a leading political force since 1975, and the Renamo party have accused each other of creating tensions.
The Renamo Party claims the government was the instigator of the latest clashes by attacking its members in the province of Sofala, the traditional stronghold of Renamo, on October 17.
The attacks on former rebels then escalated as government forces attacked Renamó bases and tried to kill Afonso Dhlakama, the group’s leader, Fernando Mazanga, a spokesman for Renamó, told the Financial Times.
The government blames Renamo for initiating clashes, accusing the party of attacking soldiers.
President Armando Gebusa has tried to dispel fears of instability.
