Power engineers of Dnipropetrovsk region have launched a unique program to save ... stork nests
In ancient times, to bring storks to the courtyard, peasants on a high pole installed a wheel from the cart, and the heavy nest held well on it.
Such special supports have not been put for a long time, so the storks chose the pillars of power lines - the intertwined branches rely on the wires, so that the real house stands securely.
Granny Anya, near whose house in the village of Ivanovka Petrikovsky district for twenty years lived a real family, began to notice how the nest settled, despite all the efforts of its inhabitants.
The birds put new branches on top, and the lower layer has already permeated between the wires, it is about to collapse.
Of course, it is a pity for the family of storks, which every year nestled in the yard, bred and fed three or four chicks during the summer, but even without light do not want to remain.
As soon as the birds flew to the warm regions, Grandma Anya called the Tsarichansky RES, which owns the support.
I didn’t expect them to react so quickly.
When our specialists arrived in Ivanovka, they were surprised that the nest still holds at all, - said the technical director of DNEPROOBLENERGO Sergey Berezovsky.
Corrosion began on the wires, which were, in fact, already inside the nest, weighing 150-200 kilograms.
At any moment, the birds could die from an electric discharge.
And the locals risked being left without light due to damage to the wires.
Therefore, linear installers began the operation to save the nest, and not for the first time in our practice.
Scientists-ornithologists from the Dnipropetrovsk National University helped, who developed a scheme for the transfer of the nest.
They also conducted trainings for employees of district networks.
The famous Dnepropetrovsk ornithologist Alexander Ponomarenko advised power engineers at all stages of the reconstruction of the nests.
To begin with, it was estimated that there are more than 50 real "apartments" in the area in an emergency state.
For their reconstruction, special metal platforms were welded, resembling a funnel.
The base was braided with willow branches, and then the old nest was moved there.
According to experts, it is enough to lay the old branches as the basis for the birds to recognize the nest and return to it.
Afterwards, the storks will build their own homes.
A month ago, the first nest was reconstructed in the village of Peschanka, Novomoskovsky district.
A new reinforced concrete pole was placed next to the electrical support and a platform with an old, already inhabited nest was placed on it.
The entire operation cost the energy in nine thousand hryvnia.
And the other day the same new settlement took place in the village of Ivanovka in the Petrikovsky district in the yard of grandma Ani.
Here the platform was fixed in the same place, only raised above the wires.
Ornithologists are sure that cautious, conservative birds will not even notice in the spring that their "apartment" has undergone major repairs.
By the end of the year, the same reconstruction awaits four more nests in the Pokrovsky and Tsarichansky districts of the Dnipropetrovsk region.
By the way, while some save rare birds, others mercilessly kill them.
Recently, the whole region flew around the sad news - in the village of Ust-Kamenka Apostolovsky district, on the day of the opening of the hunt for pheasants, poachers for entertainment shot swan family living in the local pond.
Noble birds were not afraid of people at all - the locals fed them and did not hurt them.
When the villagers, hearing the shots, ran to the pond, four beautiful swans were already lying dead on the water.
Now the staff of the Apostolovsky district police department are finding out who shot the birds listed in the Red Book.
