Obama campaign considered the exclusion of Biden in favor of Hillary Clinton
According to The New York Times, President Barack Obama’s closest advisers were secretly considering replacing Vice President Joe Biden with Hillary Clinton on the 2012 election list.
This discovery is the brightest sensation of the all-anticipated book by Mark Halperin and John Heilemann about the 2012 campaign “Bets Doubled: The Game Changed 2012”.
The Times received a copy of the forthcoming book and reported on Thursday evening that the president’s immediate aides conducted “large-scale focus group research and opinion polls in late 2011” to assess whether Biden’s exclusion could help raise waning hopes for Obama’s re-election.
According to the Times political columnist Jonathan Martin, the book gives a detailed description of the attempt by senior officials of the campaign headquarters and the White House, namely the former head of the White House administration, Bill Daley, to assess the effect on the vote of the appointment of former Secretary of State Clinton vice-president.
The possible replacement was a secret, carefully guarded at the Chicago campaign headquarters and the Oval Office.
Only six of the president’s closest advisers — including Daley, former Obama campaign chief Jim Messina, and former White House senior advisers David Axelrod and David Pluff — knew a replacement was under consideration.
The book “Bets Doubled” claims that Daley was the initiator of the attempt to replace Biden despite their “close personal relationship” but eventually abandoned the move when their data showed that adding Clinton to the electoral list would not “improve Obama’s chances substantially.”
In an interview with Martin Daley confirmed that the administration was indeed considering replacing Biden Clinton.
“I actively advocated considering a lot of things, and that was one of them,” Daley told the newspaper.
You have to remember that the president was in terrible shape at the time, so we thought, ‘Oh my God, what are we going to do?’
Although Daley described the study as a “necessary check,” Martin told CNN’s Anderson Cooper that the campaign had invested a lot in exploring whether the move would bring dividends to the vote.
“Electoral campaigns don’t spend that kind of money on polls and focus groups unless they’re taking something seriously,” Martin said in the AK 360 program.
It is unclear, however, whether Obama knew his team was exploring the possibility of a replacement.
Martin told CNN that he had asked Daley if his then-boss knew of a possible shagging.
Although Daley said he didn’t think the president “was aware” of a possible replacement, the former head of administration admitted that “perhaps” Obama knew.
Martin added that "Bets are doubled" does not give a clear answer to the question of whether the results of the political probe have reached the Obama table.
Cooper asked Martin if he seriously believed that Obama was unaware of the investigation into Biden’s exclusion from the electoral list.
“Maybe,” Martin replied.
