Halloween 2013 in Numbers
When I was a kid, Halloween was magical.
My sister and I were allowed to eat sweets, stay up late and organize a masquerade for our district.
Now I look more like a scoundrel.
I haven’t been invited to give out candy in my apartment in the last two years, and I probably won’t this year either.
However, statistics show that I am a white crow when it comes to Halloween.
According to the National Retail Federation, most Americans — 158 million — will celebrate Halloween this year and spend a total of $6.9 billion on candy, costumes and jewelry.
The only thing I look forward to every Halloween is trends.
The National Retail Federation predicts that costumes will cost $1.2 billion out of the $6.9 billion spent.
This year, sexual inanimate objects are at the peak of fashion.
Women no longer need to be sex workers; they can also be sex food, such as pizza, hamburgers, or carrots.
As for men, I think we’re going to see a lot of zombies with The Walking Dead, and I’m sure Daft Punk-style astronauts will hit our Instagram feeds this year.
According to Google, the suits that are most often searched for are zombies, Batman, pirates and witches.
There is nothing wrong with the traditional approach.
We dressed our dogs last year and, to my surprise, we weren’t the only ones.
According to the National Retail Federation, Americans will spend $330 million on pet costumes this year.
That means a lot of funny hot dogs.
When it comes to sweets, we are not trivial.
Americans will spend $1.9 billion on them this year, according to Nielsen.
That’s about 600 million pounds of Hershey chocolates, lollipops, Milk Duds candies, Twizzlers chewable candies, and Clark Bar bars.
According to the U.S. Department of Commerce, this is great news for the 41 million candy-demanding children who have prepared to conquer our neighborhoods.
Moreover, we will buy and – let’s not fool ourselves – eat 90 million pounds of chocolate during Halloween.
The only thing we don’t want to eat is corn grain-shaped candies; and yet, according to the National Confectionery Association, nearly <0xC2><0xA3>35 million of them are sold on Halloween.
That’s about 9 billion individual corn grains.
This is a mystery that I still have to solve.
Nothing expresses the essence of Halloween like a ghost house.
They have amazing titles, such as “Horror Behind the Walls” (which, incidentally, is in a real prison), “Shout and Scream” and “House of Shock”.
Moreover, according to America Haunts, there are 1,200 officially recognized ghost houses in America, generating about $500 million in revenue, as well as those amazing photos where you almost peed, which your friend posted on Facebook and you can not remove, and then the guy who you like, sees this photo and leaves a comment like "classy facial expression".
Finally, let’s talk about pumpkins.
Charlie Brown introduced us to the Great Pumpkin when we were kids, and carving Jack’s lamp is like decorating a Christmas tree, something we’ve been doing since childhood.
Luckily for us, the baby pumpkin fashion only started last year thanks to Pinterest, so most of us grew up carving these pumpkins instead of sitting in them.
According to the U.S. Census Bureau, Americans will spend about $106 million on pumpkins this year.
Jack’s lamp, slowly drying out on your porch, probably came from Illinois, which has grown 542 million pounds of pumpkin this year.
If you want harder tasks, visit Tim and Susan Mathisdon in Napa, California, and try cutting out something from their 2032-pound pumpkin.
