George Kerevan: a break with Europe gives the Scots a choice
Another day, another horror story about independence.
This time, we are warned that an independent Scotland will have to join a pan-European free movement area as a condition of EU membership.
There is a series of stories about passport control in Berwick and the barbed wire border along Hadrian’s Wall.
However, the Strathclyde newspaper pointed to the possible economic benefits of freer movements across the rest of Europe, although – as predictable – this did not appear in the headlines.
Neither has anyone pointed out that EU member states spend a lot of time to turn their formal rules around as they please.
Since Scotland is not currently part of the Schengen area, continuing non-compliance would be a cheap concession for Brussels in return for what it really wanted from the Scots.
This is not a worthy story.
And so old that it turned into a fossil: the first time I heard a “duck” that “independence means passport control” was at least 40 years ago.
And yet there is an interesting moment lost in the retelling of an old fairy tale.
Why does an independent Scotland have to obey Europe’s orders?
Why change the yoke of London to the yoke of Brussels, especially now?
Here is the real European news: the great post-war plan to unite Europe has finally stalled.
With the euro crisis, the Europe project is officially dead.
Throughout the European Union, parties opposed to the EU or in favour of the abolition of the euro as a single currency are gaining strength.
Even in Germany, the Eurosceptic party Alternative for Germany – founded just this year – emerged out of nowhere and garnered nearly five million votes in the September federal election, thus essentially ousting the Free Democrats (analogue to our Liberal Democrats) from the Bundestag.
There has always been an internal opposition to the plan to create a federal Europe.
Nevertheless, the current economic crisis has been a turning point.
The austerity measures imposed by Berlin and the European Central Bank, and the shackles imposed on national economies through the preservation of the single currency, have led many people to think that the Europe project has gone too far.
The euro crisis has little to do with the fact that national governments operate with excessive budget deficits – this was true only for Greece.
In fact, the Eurosystem has blocked its members at exchange rates favourable to German exporters – which German politicians want to keep.
Without the possibility of devaluation of the national currency, southern Europe finds itself at a pre-emptive disadvantage in terms of production opportunities compared to Germany.
The only way to save money is to cut salaries and government spending, which is actively supported by Berlin.
Behind the current problems of the budget and the currency lies the deeper problem of Europe’s productive capacity.
As a result of the set of green energy measures implemented by Brussels – a cipher that means subsidizing French and German energy companies at the expense of the consumer – European industry pays twice as much for electricity and four times more for gas than in the United States.
These are paralyzingly unfavourable price conditions, as we have seen in Grangemouth.
No wage freezes in the world will stop the crushing victory of cheap U.S. shale gas over the European petrochemical industry.
As a result, a revolt is ripening, especially in France, once the most ardent supporter of the EU.
After the war, the French political elite saw the EU as a way to control Germany and put Paris on par with Washington.
But Berlin no longer needs Paris as a means of gaining political legitimacy, and has already imposed its own economic policy on Europe, leaving France’s ruined economy in dire straits.
The result is that Marine Le Pen’s right-wing anti-EU National Front party has just won a decisive additional election, dropping the ruling Socialist Party to third place.
The Front is now the most popular party in France with 24 percent of the vote – a timely warning to British Labour that it cannot be assumed that a split between the right will automatically affect the left.
What does Le Pen do with his newfound popularity among the French white working class?
She wants to use the EU elections next year to create a bloc in the European Parliament against the EU and against the single currency.
If - and it is very likely - anti-EU parties gain support in this election, such a bloc will be able to take a dominant position in the European Parliament for the first time.
This is my opinion: soon the growing sentiment against the EU and against the single currency in Europe will merge to destroy the euro.
The EU will not disappear, but it will again become something like the vague “Europe of (sovereign) nations” that General de Gaulle liked.
Germany and several of its dependent economies could save the euro, but France and southern Europe would rebuild their own currencies.
I assume that the UK is distancing itself from this project, hoping to get closer to the US.
Yet Washington’s growing interest in the Pacific indicates the likelihood that Britain will be left unattended in the cold Atlantic.
In what position does this leave Scotland?
We can choose to become a region (in fact) of Little England.
Or we can defend our own economic interests, which means, among other things, sending Berlin and Brussels to hell.
I suspect Scotland will be able to thrive under a freer European arrangement, provided we keep our currency.
Cooperation with other like-minded countries will be easier in a non-federal Europe of nations.
Otherwise, we should consider repeating Norway's experience and preserving our economic independence.
The government of the Scottish National Party in Scotland is, oddly enough, the most successful political movement in Europe against austerity, which won an impressive majority in 2011 thanks to objections to spending cuts proposed (and implemented) by Labour Chancellor of the Treasury Aleister Darling and the subsequent Tory and Liberal Democrat coalition.
It would be ridiculous for Scotland now to vote for independence just to take the austerity measures imposed by Berlin and Brussels.
Early Puberty: Ageing Earlier
African-American and Latino girls tend to reach puberty earlier than their white peers, research shows.
Physical changes do not mean that puberty is near
There is no evidence that hormones or other chemicals are to blame.
Experts believe that the obesity epidemic may be one of the triggers of early puberty
The tendency to early puberty is not so pronounced in boys
Former CNN correspondent Pat Etheridge is a journalist specializing in children's health and family issues.
Should a mother be afraid if her daughter begins to form the rudiments of the breast and grow pubic hair at 7 or 8 years old?
At the annual conference of the American Academy of Pediatrics this week in Orlando, Florida, pediatric endocrinologist Dr. Paul Kaplowitz explained that these early physical changes are quite common among American girls and represent a new norm.
“I spend a lot of time reassuring parents — usually that doesn’t mean full puberty is coming soon,” Kaplowitz said.
Obvious signs of development, such as growing breasts, pubic and axillary hair, and body odor, appear earlier in girls.
But there has been only a slight shift in age in menarche (the first menstruation) over the past four decades.
In the United States, the average age is 12.5 years, down from 12.75 in 1970.
“Once the breast begins to develop, it’s at least two to three years before menarche,” said Kaplowitz, who is also the author of Early Puberty in Girls: How to Deal with This Common Problem.
Time is the most accurate test of how puberty will progress.
There is a debate about what constitutes the actual onset of puberty, but is considered "premature" when breast augmentation is accompanied by a sharp increase in height up to 8 years.
In most cases, the process will slow down or pause — this is something that a pediatrician can monitor closely.
Faster progression can serve as a basis for tests by an endocrinologist to rule out serious problems such as tumors or cysts.
There are procedures to delay early menstruation and prevent another consequence: premature bone aging, which can eventually lead to slow growth and low growth in adulthood.
Recommendations for drug or hormone therapy are based on the child’s age, level of development, growth rate and emotional maturity.
The psychosocial aspects are also important.
Kaplowitz is cautious about drugs, but admits that “suppression of puberty can mitigate the behavioral problems and feelings of girls that they are different from their peers.”
Another big problem is understandable: parents simply do not want their very young daughters to have menstruation.
“They’re worried about the risk of pregnancy or even how they’re going to deal with hygiene issues,” Kaplowitz said.
“It was a shock,” recalls one woman whose daughter began menstruating at the age of 10.
Although there were signs and we talked about menstruation, she was not emotionally ready.
She came home from school frightened and upset that she was the first among her friends.
There are many publicized theories about the causes of early puberty.
However, there is no consistent evidence that hormones in milk or other foods, chemicals in the environment, or sexual messages in the media are to blame.
In boys, as in girls, puberty occurs earlier.
Kaplowitz argues that the premise that has the greatest weight is the obesity epidemic.
In 2001, he helped carry out a study on girls between the ages of 6 and 9, which linked the amount of body fat to puberty.
Other data support this conclusion, but there are many other contributing factors.
In this country, African-American and Latino girls tend to reach puberty earlier than their white peers.
There are various explanations.
All over the world, early puberty seems to be affected by everything from economic conditions and climate to genes.
Another mystery: although boys have facial and pubic hair at a younger age, the tendency to full early puberty is not as pronounced as in girls.
Other doctors attending the AAP conference confirmed the complexity of the topic.
The appearance of acne and pubic hair occurs even in infants and children of nursery age.
“We have to be careful about how we determine the true onset of puberty,” said Dr. Lawrence Silverman, a pediatric endocrinologist at Children’s Hospital Gorieb in Morristown, New Jersey.
Parents should not be embarrassed to receive instructions from a pediatrician about how to talk to their child.
“This could mean an earlier-than-expected conversation,” Kaplowitz explained.
If you stay calm, your child will usually respond well.
Girls who bloom early need confirmation that even when it happens early, this process is a normal part of life.
