Singapore pawnshop owners are doing well while the middle class is struggling
In a pawnshop in Bendemir shopping center in Singapore, Janani Amirthalinga lays a gold bracelet, a ring and earrings to pay for her daughter’s schooling.
“My husband and I just bought a house, so all my money is invested there,” says Amirthalinga.
Although she earns S$3,000 ($2,400) a month as an administrator and her husband also works, the family’s monthly income is not enough, she says.
Indeed, demand in various parts of Southeast Asia — where household debt is growing — is such that ValueMax, where it conducts its transaction, this week became the third pawnshop listed on the Singapore Stock Exchange.
A Jewelry Loan is not just a quick way to get money (S$1300 in the case of Ms. Amirthalinga), but it’s almost as cheap as unsecured bank loans.
Usually, pawnbrokers in Singapore charge an effective annual interest rate of 17% – just above the 15.4% offered at the United Overseas Bank branch, a local lender with a branch in the same mall.
However, pawnshops have the advantage that they do not require credit checks or proof of salary and can issue loans faster than banks.
Therefore, millions of people across the region are turning to pawnshops as families feel pressured by the rising cost of living and the rapid growth of household debt and consumer debt.
After five years of sustained growth following the global financial crisis and cheap credit fueled by free monetary policy in advanced economies, low- and middle-income families turn to pawnshops to offset declining incomes as their economies slow down.
This week, Standard & Poor’s, a rating agency, pointed to the increase in family leverage, mainly due to the rise in mortgages, as a risk factor for the creditworthiness of Asian banks.
It stated that Malaysia, Thailand and Singapore had the highest debt-to-GDP ratios of households in Asia.
Malaysia topped the list with 80% of GDP, up from 60% in 2008.
Economists are also concerned about Thailand’s high levels of consumer debt, which barely emerged from a technical recession this week.
On Thursday, the data showed a continued decline in exports and weakening consumer demand.
“The bottom line is that with rising prices, people in the middle and bottom [income scale] will be looking for ways to replenish their income wherever they can,” says Song Seng Woon, an economist at CIMB, a Malaysian bank.
Record high gold prices in the last two years have intensified the rush with which people pawn their personal belongings as they seize the opportunity to get money for their family jewelry.
In Singapore, about 70% of the items laid in the 200 pawn shops of the city-state are gold products.
People say, “The price of gold looks good, let’s lay the grandmother’s gold chain and get it back next month.”
In Thailand, the largest pawnshop operator EasyMoney has seen the number of customers using its offices grow in recent months up to 20%.
The growth in the pawnshop business is such that ValueMax, the operator of the branch in Bendemir and 15 others in Singapore, plans to expand not only in neighboring Malaysia, where it has four stores, but also outside Asia, says Yeah Lee Ching, CEO of ValueMax.
The company will finance the expansion using 60 percent of the S$66 million raised this week as a result of the Singapore Stock Exchange.
While some lenders have sparked a fire of criticism due to high interest rates, Ms. Yeah says the pawnshop not only offers cheaper rates than other lenders, it also does not increase debt directly.
“Customers lay down items they already own, and monetizing personal assets does not increase household debt,” she says.
The institution is gaining increasing public recognition as a means of obtaining short-term, secured financing.
At the same time pawnshops are used not only by those categories of people who are in a difficult financial situation.
Rich people in Singapore also use ValueMax branches by pawning gold bars or Rolex watches, which can give up to 60 percent of their purchase value in cash.
We see clients from all walks of life.
“They include wealthy individuals who need to borrow money for a short period of time for commercial projects or investments, or small businesses who need to overcome temporary cash difficulties,” says Ms. Yeah.
Sometimes they just need the money very quickly.
