Thus, there is still no “Words with Friends” — an intelligent Internet game that actor Alec Baldwin played on his smartphone in 2011, when there was a notorious case: the actor was taken off the plane of American Airlines for refusing to turn off the device while the plane was at the gate.
And heavier devices, such as laptops, will still need to be stacked in the luggage compartment, as they can injure someone if they fly all over the cabin.
Calls from mobile phones in flight will also be prohibited.
Regulatory powers for telephone calls are vested in the Federal Communications Commission, not the FAA.
FAU may lift ban on some electronic devices during take-off and landing
Last month, Mark Rosenker of the National Transportation Safety Board, a national transport safety expert at CBS News, said cell phones were still considered a risk.
“Cell phones are really a problem, not only because they have the potential to create interference for navigation devices, but we know through the FCC that they can create interference for cell towers when the plane is in the air,” Rosenker said.
An industry advisory committee set up by the FAA to examine the issue recommended last month that the government allow more use of personal electronic devices.
In recent years, there has been increasing pressure on FAAs to ease restrictions on their use.
Critics such as Missouri Democratic Senator Claire McCasquill argue that there are no compelling security reasons for the bans.
Compliance with restrictions is also becoming increasingly difficult to ensure as the use of devices has become ubiquitous.
Some studies show that up to a third of passengers forget or ignore instructions to turn off their devices.
The FAA began restricting the use of electronic devices by passengers in 1966 in response to reports of interference to navigation and communication equipment, when passengers began carrying FM radios, high-tech gadgets of the time.
New airliners are much more dependent on electrical systems than previous generations of aircraft, but they are also developed and approved by the FAA as resistant to electronic interference.
Airlines have been offering passengers the use of Wi-Fi at cruise altitude for several years.
Aircraft modified for Wi-Fi systems are also more resistant to interference.
The vast majority of the liners are adapted for wider use of electronic devices under the new guidelines, Huerta said.
Today’s electronic devices typically emit radio signals of much lower power than previous generations of devices.
Devices for reading e-books, for example, emit only minimal signals when scrolling pages.
But signals become more powerful when devices load or send data.
Among those who sought to ease restrictions on the use of electronic devices by passengers was Amazon.com.
In 2011, the company loaded an entire airliner with its Kindle e-book readers and flew on it to check for problems, but never found them.
FAU Advisory Committee members expressed mixed feelings as to whether the use of the devices posed any risk.
Douglas Kidd of the National Air Passenger Association said he believes interference from devices is real, even if the risk is minimal.
Other members of the committee said there were only individual pilot reports confirming that the devices could create interference to aviation systems, and most of these reports are very old.
However, the committee recommended that the FAA allow pilots to require passengers to disconnect devices during instrument landings in restricted visibility conditions.
