Is Europe’s elite ready to do business with England?
The Business for Britain campaign was launched in April with a commitment to bring together business representatives and determine what changes the UK’s wealth and jobs creators want to see in their relationship with the EU.
To this end, we commissioned the largest and most comprehensive survey of British business leaders, asking them to express their thoughts on the UK, business and the EU.
YouGov surveyed more than 1,000 business leaders representing a wide range of businesses in the UK by size, sector and region.
The results of the survey will come as a surprise to many.
We found that the vast majority of businesses are currently looking for opportunities to export outside of Europe, paying particular attention to countries that are modernizing and growing while EU countries are stagnant.
They want the government to prioritize new trade ties with countries like China, India and Brazil, rather than wasting time on the long and arduous process of reforming the intricate EU institutions.
When asked about their views on specific policy issues, from antitrust regulation to product laws, most business leaders felt that control of these key areas of competence should be returned to Westminster.
There was general dissatisfaction with the single market, with business representatives saying that the costs of regulation from Brussels now outweigh the benefits of being in the European trade zone, even 40 percent of large enterprises, traditionally the most pro-European of all companies, agreed with this.
Last but not least, our survey of business leaders revealed that an overwhelming majority wants the UK to pursue a trade-based rather than policy-based approach to treaty change and relations with the EU.
This result, which has been seen among businesses of all sizes and the largest business groups, shows that the business is pushing for a “significant change” that will bring authority back to the UK.
The stakes are high – achieving treaty changes and more favourable terms for the UK would provide a 16 percent shift in voting to stay in the EU.
The prime minister should have no doubts: this survey shows that British business supports his plan to revise the terms of Britain’s EU membership.
It also shows that business expects the revision to lead to a significant shift in the current balance of power back towards the UK.
Better conditions for British business are possible and increasingly necessary as the eurozone embarks on a path of closer economic and financial integration.
Priority should be given to jobs and economic growth in the UK, and, as our survey shows, for businesses, this means an increased focus on trade and fundamental changes in Brussels’ regulatory activity.
