Scientists have shed light on how the movements of the dog's tail are related to its mood.
Previous studies have shown that satisfied dogs wag their tails to the right (from a dog’s point of view), while anxious dogs wag their tails predominantly to the left.
But now scientists say that other members of the canine family may notice these subtle differences in tail-drilling and respond to them.
Professor Giorgio Vallortigara, a neuroscientist at the University of Trent, says: “It is well known that in humans, the left and right sides of the brain participate differently in the formation of stimuli that cause positive or negative emotions.”
Here we tried to look at this and other species.
He added that just like humans, dogs have the right side of the brain that controls the left side of the body and vice versa, and the two hemispheres play different roles in emotions.
To learn more about how dogs respond to the versatile tailings of other dogs, the researchers observed the animals when they watched movies about other dogs.
They measured the heart rate of animals and analyzed their behavior.
It is likely that soon we will understand why their tails are sometimes directed in one direction, and sometimes in the other.
Professor Vallortigara said: “We showed the dogs videos with the dogs – either naturalistic versions or a silhouette to get rid of any other distortions, and we could manipulate the movement of the tail and point the tail more to the left or to the right.”
When the animals saw that the otherwise unexpressing dog was moving the tail to the right (from the point of view of the wagging dog), they remained completely relaxed.
But when they noticed that the tail tilted mainly to the left (again from the point of view of a wagging dog), their heartbeat increased and they looked alarmed.
Professor Vallortigara said he did not think the dogs intentionally communicated with each other through these movements.
In fact, he believes that dogs have learned from their experience which movements they should be worried about and which they shouldn’t.
He observes: “If there are multiple encounters with other dogs, and often their tails roll in one direction is associated with more friendly behavior, and the right side gives less friendly behavior, then the dog reacts based on this experience.”
The researchers say these findings could give owners, veterinarians and trainers a deeper understanding of their animal’s emotions.
Dog behavior expert John Bradshaw, a visiting researcher at the University of Bristol Veterinary School, said this was not the first study to test whether the left and right sides matter to dogs.
Last year, a group of scientists from Lincoln University found that dogs turn their heads to the left if they look at an aggressive dog, and to the right if they look at a satisfied dog.
And in another study at the University of Victoria in Canada, he reported: “Dogs were more likely to approach a robot dog when the whirl of its tail was directed to the left rather than to the right, instead of becoming anxious, the opposite behavior to the Italian study.”
He said the differences may have been due to the fact that dogs in various studies did not fully perceive animals in movies or robot dogs as dogs.
It could be useful to study how dogs react to real dogs, he explained.
"While there is sufficient evidence for different mammals that the two hemispheres of the brain are used for different purposes, many details have yet to be clarified, and dogs are no exception," he said.
However, given the ease with which their behavior can be recorded, we will probably soon understand why their tails sometimes point in one direction and sometimes in the other.
