Pope Francis to name first cardinals in February
Pope Francis will raise new cardinals to the Catholic Church for the first time in his term of office on February 22, the Vatican announced on Thursday.
Cardinals are the highest clergy in the Catholic Church after the pope, and it is they who elect the popes, so Francis will appoint his first group of people who will ultimately participate in the election of his successor.
There are currently 201 cardinals.
However, after reaching the age of 80, he can no longer participate in the election of the pope - this is the prerogative of a group of 120 "electoral cardinals".
Announcing the news, Vatican spokesman Father Federico Lombardi said that a meeting of all current cardinals, known as the consistory, would be held before the inauguration ceremony.
“Pope Francis has decided to announce in advance his decision to convene a consistory in February in order to facilitate the planning of other meetings with the participation of cardinals from different parts of the world,” Lombardi said.
Jack Valero of Catholic Voices said the number of cardinal voters is likely to decline by February.
He said it is customary for the pope to name as many cardinals as necessary to bring the number of cardinal electors back to 120, as well as as many cardinals over the age of 80 as he wishes.
The consistory next year will make a big difference because it will be the first since Francis was elected in March this year, Valero said.
At the moment, there is a kind of bias in favor of Europe and especially in favor of Italy.
“It will be interesting to see if the new pope will appoint cardinals from other regions of the world to restore balance,” he said.
Forty percent of Catholics live in South America, but they are represented by a small number of cardinals.
They will also be the first elected cardinals since Francis formed the Council of Cardinals, a group of eight cardinals from around the world tasked with seeking ways to reform the church.
In the past, my dad made his own decisions.
“Now Francis has chosen eight cardinals to help him,” Valero said.
He said it was “very possible” that Francis would turn to the cardinals for advice.
But we have not been in this situation before - this is all for us for the first time.
Valero said that the popes usually raised the cardinal bishops from large parishes, but Francis is “full of surprises – so we don’t know who he’ll name.”
GM recalls a number of new pickups in the United States to refine the seat backs
General Motors Co. is recalling nearly 19,000 all-new 2014 Chevrolet Silverado and GMC Sierra pickup trucks to address issues with manually adjustable backrest tilts, according to a notice from U.S. vehicle safety regulators on Friday.
On some of the pickups, the front seats may have a defect in the back tilt mechanism.
As a result, the seat backs do not meet the federal safety standards for head restraints.
“When a car is hit from behind, the head restraint may not adequately protect the driver and passengers, increasing the risk of injury,” the National Highway Traffic Safety Administration said in a notice posted on its website.
The recalled models were manufactured in the period from August 1 to September 10.
The launch of GM pickup trucks began in June and represents the most important launch of the car into serial production for the leading American automaker since its restructuring due to bankruptcy in 2009.
GM informed pickup owners of the defect in the first half of October.
The National Highway Traffic Safety Administration could not consider notifying owners due to the government’s 16-day shutdown, which reduced car sales growth in October.
Sales of the Silverado and Sierra pickup trucks, which were upgraded for the 2014 model year, grew by about 20 percent during the first 10 months of this year, GM said on Friday.
In October, GM sold 42,660 Silverado pickup trucks and 16,503 Sierra pickup trucks.
GM shares on the New York Stock Exchange on Friday afternoon rose by 1.4 percent to $37.47.
The Cries of Obama’s Voter
I voted for President Obama twice, sharing the hope of change.
He says Obama has allowed Republican obstructionism to nullify the laudable effort.
Obstructionism Cannot Justify Problems With Obama’s Reformed Healthcare Website, Drone Attacks
Obama’s 2008 campaign memoirs are a sad reminder of what might have been.
Nathaniel P. Morris is a second-year medical student at Harvard University.
I am reading a very sad book these days.
I thought this book would inspire me in my second year of medical school, and give me a sense of hope.
It’s called “Courage to Win,” and it’s a memoir of Barack Obama’s 2008 presidential campaign.
When I finish writing my patient reports in the evening and go to bed, this book takes me back to a time when politics inspired millions of people and speeches were breathtaking.
The election victory was impressive, and news anchors paused to reflect on this historic moment.
My classmates were crying with joy, and my parents were guarding every newspaper they could find.
A young team of strategists was to come to the White House, and the people were ready for change.
When Obama took office in 2008, his support rate was 82%.
Then I close the book.
Returning to the present is a rough awakening, like pulling out of a dream.
It’s hard to remember those days of optimism – they seem like a distant memory, a sad reminder of missed opportunities.
In the years since I dropped my first ballot, the changes have really happened.
It was something I couldn't even imagine.
I pay tribute to Obama for his great and varied achievements, from the adoption of the Affordable Care Act to the withdrawal of our military from Iraq, the repeal of the “Don’t Ask, Don’t Tell” rule, the assassination of Osama bin Laden.
Moreover, I believe that party obstructionism has blocked too many attempts to move our country forward: immigration reform, the ability to choose public health care, and the closure of Guantanamo Bay, among others.
But after countless times I’ve been on the side of the Obama administration, defending it to colleagues and peers, I’ve run out of explanations that I can provide.
I have reached a point of political despair.
Republican obstructionism cannot explain the permission to wiretap foreign leaders or drone strikes on innocent children in other countries.
It cannot explain the collection of data on Americans’ privacy by the National Security Agency or the prosecution of whistleblowers who expose government misconduct.
He cannot explain the murder of U.S. citizen Anwar al-Awlaki without trial and investigation, or the failure to comply with the limits of state funding and spending during presidential campaigns.
He cannot justify the findings of the report, which says the White House’s efforts to silence the media are “the most aggressive ... since the Nixon administration.”
And lately, he can’t justify not being able to develop a simple website for more than three years after signing the Affordable Care Act.
I don't know if I should have expected that.
Should I have understood at the age of 18 that leadership can contradict the political campaigns that precede it?
Obviously, working in an elected position is not a predictable program of action, since our public dialogue will be shaped by an opposition political party and such random events as the Newtown massacre.
Nonetheless, all of the examples I have cited above show that they were largely the administration's own choice.
And that's what worries me the most.
I voted for Obama again in 2012, but not because I was enthusiastic about his candidacy.
Mitt Romney was an incomprehensible and crude alternative, he seemed unable to make decisions about his own policies or views.
I believed that in his second term, Obama, freed from the pressure of future elections, would live up to the hopes we had heard about for so long.
However, when Obama’s rating dropped below 45% this week, it became much harder to go back to 2008 with this book.
It makes me long for a lot of promises that have gone away.
This week, I read the part of the book that describes how Clinton inflicted a deafening defeat on Obama in the Pennsylvania primary.
At the failure analysis meeting, he told his staff that they should return to normal and remain true to their goal.
“I want us to regain our attractiveness,” he said.
We have to remember who we are.”
Five years have passed, Mr. President, and I fully agree with you.
The views expressed in this commentary belong exclusively to Nathaniel Morris.
