RBS suspends two foreign exchange traders
The Royal Bank of Scotland has suspended two traders in its foreign exchange division, according to two people familiar with the situation, further confirming that global scrutiny by regulators of alleged currency market manipulation is gaining momentum.
Some of the world’s largest banks, including UBS, Barclays, Deutsche Bank and RBS, have confirmed that they are cooperating with regulators in investigations related to the world’s largest financial market, whose daily turnover is $5.3 trillion.
The two traders will be the first RBS employees to be suspended in an unfolding investigation that echoes the LIBOR interbank rate manipulation scandal.
Refusing to comment on the suspension, the bank confirmed that it had received requests for information from regulators this month.
“Our ongoing investigation into this matter is ongoing and we are fully cooperating with the FCA and our other regulators,” the bank said in a statement two weeks ago.
Last month, insiders said RBS handed over email and instant messaging records received and sent by its former trader to the UK’s financial regulator, the Financial Conduct Authority (FCA).
This trader, Richard Usher, left RBS in 2010 and is known to have been granted leave of absence in his current position as head of European spot currency trading at JPMorgan.
Rohan Ramchandani, head of European spot trading at Citi, went on vacation this week, while Matt Gardiner, a former senior currency trader at Barclays and UBS, was suspended from work by Standard Chartered this week.
None of these traders have been charged with any wrongdoing.
Mr. Usher’s instant messaging contact group included bankers from Barclays and Citigroup, according to knowledgeable individuals.
UBS said this week it had taken action against some of its employees after Swiss regulator Finma said it was investigating alleged currency market manipulation at a number of Swiss banks.
At least six regulators around the world — the European Commission, Finma, Swiss antitrust authority Weko, FCA, the U.S. Department of Justice and the Hong Kong Monetary Authority — are reviewing allegations that bankers colluded to influence the foreign exchange market.
HSBC, Citigroup, JPMorgan and Credit Suisse have also started internal audits or received requests for information from regulators, people familiar with the situation said.
Banks have been reviewing instant messages and emails for several years in search of offenses.
The news of the inspections has stirred up traders in the sphere of activity, which in recent years has been one of the largest sources of income of the trading divisions of investment banks, which, however, this year faced difficulties due to the fact that low currency volatility reduces favorable opportunities for buyers.
Some bankers have tried to downplay the seriousness of the situation by saying that an extensive and highly liquid foreign exchange market is almost impossible to manipulate, but senior traders say this is not always true.
According to the senior trader, despite the huge volume of daily trading in the foreign exchange market, the fragmentation of liquidity between different trading platforms and the wider use by banks of their internal platforms means that “you can start to influence the market for a very small price.”
The news came on the same day that Credit Suisse announced it had fired one of the traders in its London Stock Exchange trading department this week after it caused nearly $6 million in losses late last year.
The Bank shall immediately notify the relevant authorities and cooperate with its regulators.
“We are confident that the trader acted alone and that this issue has been localized,” Credit Suisse said.
