Google, Samsung, Huawei sued for Nortel patents
The group, which owns thousands of former Nortel patents, filed a series of patent lawsuits on Thursday against mobile phone makers, including Google, which it broke at an auction for Nortel’s bankruptcy.
The Rockstar consortium, which bought Nortel patents for $4.5 billion, has filed patent infringement lawsuits in a U.S. District Court in Texas against Samsung Electronics Co Ltd, HTC Corp, Huawei and four other companies.
Rockstar is jointly owned by Apple, Microsoft, Blackberry, Ericsson and Sony.
Google has been accused of infringing seven patents.
These patents cover technologies that help match online search keywords to relevant ads, the lawsuit says, which is the backbone of Google’s search business.
Representatives of Samsung, Huawei, HTC and Rockstar were unavailable and did not comment.
Samsung, Huawei and HTC make phones running the Android operating system from Google, which competes fiercely with mobile products from Apple and Microsoft.
In 2011, Google offered an initial price of $900 million for Nortel patents.
Google raised the price several times, eventually offering as much as $4.4 billion.
