Egypt sworn in as first freely elected president
Mohamed Morsi is sworn in, but the day of his triumph is unlikely to mark the end of the political struggle in Egypt.
Islamist Mohammed Morsi promised a “new Egypt” when he took the oath of office, becoming the country’s first freely elected president, replacing Hosni Mubarak, who was ousted 16 months ago.
At his inauguration before the Supreme Constitutional Court, Morsi also became the first freely elected Islamist president of the Arab world and the fifth head of state in Egypt since the overthrow of the monarchy some 60 years ago.
He was sworn in before 18 judges in black robes in a courthouse on the banks of the Nile, built in the style of an ancient Egyptian temple.
“We are looking for a better future, a new Egypt and a second republic,” Morsi said during a ceremony broadcast live on state television.
“Today, the Egyptian people have laid the foundations for a new life – absolute freedom, genuine democracy and stability,” said Morsi, a 60-year-old engineer with an American education from the Muslim Brotherhood, a fundamentalist group that for most of its 84 years of existence has been a banned organization that has served as a target for harsh actions by successive governments.
The building was guarded by hundreds of soldiers and police when Morsi arrived with a small convoy shortly after 11 a.m. local time.
Only a few hundred supporters gathered outside the courthouse to welcome the new president, and unlike the Mubarak-era presidential pump, traffic was halted for only a short time to let his convoy pass along the normally busy road connecting the city centre with the southern suburbs.
Although mocked as a non-charismatic “spare wheel” of the Brothers, Morsi’s personal prestige has risen dramatically since his victory and Friday’s performance in which he tried to present himself as a candidate not only for Islamists but for all those who want to bring to an end the 2011 uprising against authoritarian Mubarak.
“Today Egypt is a civil, national, constitutional and modern state,” Morsi, dressed in a blue business suit with a red tie, told the judges in the wooden paneled hall where he took the oath.
Morsi later went to the University of Cairo, where he was to deliver his inaugural speech.
He was given an official reception with the army orchestra, performing the national anthem, during which he stood on the stand "peacefully".
Field Marshal Hussein Tantawi was present.
His arrival was greeted by the slogan "Army and people - one hand", which was chanted by hundreds of people gathered in the main lecture hall of the university.
Founded in 1908 as a stronghold of secular education, Cairo University in the 1970s became a stronghold of Islamist student groups.
Morsi took a symbolic oath Friday in Tahrir Square, where an uprising broke out that ended Mubarak’s authoritarian rule last year, and promised to regain the presidency, which had been stripped of his office by a military council that took cases from the ousted leader.
But by agreeing to take a formal oath before a court rather than parliament, as is customary, he is fulfilling the military’s will, and this is a sign that the power struggle will continue.
Morsi’s speech in Tahrir Square was filled with theatrical populist gestures.
