A trip through mud, rivers and jungles to provide free medical care
Dr. Georges Bvelle provides free health care in rural Cameroon
Bwell and his team spend almost every weekend taking in hundreds of patients.
In this West African country, there are not many doctors — only one in 5,000 people
Vote here or through your mobile device
Dr. Georges Bvelle is one of the 10 main characters of CNN in 2013.
You can vote for him or any of the other 10 main characters to make him a CNN Hero of the Year.
This person will receive $250,000 to continue his outstanding work.
For 21 years, Georges Bvelle saw his father come back to life and again fall unconscious, wandering through hospitals that were not properly equipped to help him.
Jamef Bvelle was injured in a car accident in 1981 near Yaoundé, the capital of Cameroon.
At first, he only had a broken arm, but the resulting infection spread to the brain and caused a hematoma that resembled him for the rest of his life.
“There were no neurosurgeons in Cameroon,” said Georges Bvelle.
If we had the money, we would have taken him out of Cameroon.
Instead, Bwelle accompanied his father for years to overcrowded clinics and hospitals, receiving whatever treatment they could get.
“It’s not easy,” Bwell said.
You can leave home at 5 a.m., run to the hospital to be the first, but you are not the first.
There are a lot of patients.
Some may die because they have to wait.
The situation hasn’t changed much since Bwell’s father died in 2002.
According to the World Health Organization, there is only one doctor for every 5,000 people in Cameroon.
For comparison, the ratio in the United States is one doctor per 413 people.
And even if Cameroonians could see a doctor, many of them would be out of pocket.
Two out of five people in the country live below the poverty line, and nearly three-quarters of the country’s healthcare spending is private.
“Their only problem is poverty,” Bwelle said.
“And because of poverty, they can’t enjoy their lives.”
Seeing the suffering of his father and many of his compatriots, Bvelle was determined to do something about it.
Last year, Dr. Georges Bvelle and his team of volunteers performed 700 free surgeries.
He himself became a doctor and works as a vascular surgeon at Yaoundé Central Hospital.
He also founded the non-profit organization ASCOVIME, which organizes trips to the countryside on weekends to provide free medical care.
Since 2008, he and his group of volunteers have assisted nearly 32,000 people.
Almost every Friday, he and up to 30 other people are stuffed into vans, tie medical supplies to rooftops, and travel across rough terrain to visit villages in need.
They are not always lucky.
More than once they had to push cars across rivers and dirt.
But when they arrive, they are greeted like real heroes: it’s a holiday with songs and dances and the best rooms the locals have to offer.
The free medical care in these villages is indeed a cause for celebration, and Bvelle with its wide smile and boundless energy is more than happy to join in the fun.
The next morning, the team starts taking in hundreds of patients.
“We take 500 people on every trip,” Bvelle said.
They come from all over the county within a radius of 60 kilometers from the village, and they come on foot.
Each of these weekend clinics provides a variety of medical services.
Many people receive treatment for malaria, tuberculosis, malnutrition, diabetes, parasites and sexually transmitted diseases.
Others may get crutches, donated points, or free birth certificates—documents required for school that many poor families simply can’t afford.
In the evening, the brigade conducts simple operations under local anesthesia.
Surgery is usually done in a school building, municipality or home; after the procedure, patients get up and go to the post-surgery area to make room for the next person.
Using a generator to illuminate the operating and sanitation equipment, Bvelle and his volunteers work until early Sunday morning.
It’s an unbearable pace, but the dedication of the brigade usually helps support the village musicians.
“They’re drumming all night to keep us awake and working,” Bvelle said.
On Sunday, members of the brigade are sent back to the city, tired but proud of their work.
This group, consisting of Cameroonian doctors and international medical students, has conducted 700 free surgeries over the past year and they know that their help can make a huge difference to those they help.
One person explained that the free hernia surgery he received would allow him to work again.
“It will change the future for me and my family,” he said.
In addition to these weekend clinics and hospital work, Bwelle also works at night in private medical clinics around Yaoundé.
It is this second work, he said, that provides 60% of the funding for his non-profit organization; the rest of the funds are covered by private donations.
“I don’t even know when he’s sleeping,” said Katie O’Malley, a second-year medical student at Drexel University in Philadelphia, a volunteer in Bwell’s group.
He is always either in the hospital or trying to earn money for the organization so that these campaigns can continue.
For future doctors and nurses like O’Malley coming from the U.S. and Europe to join Bwell in carrying out his tasks, this is an opportunity of practice that they would never have gotten at home.
“We got the opportunity to assist in operations where we helped remove blood stains or hold instruments for Dr. Bwell,” O’Malley said.
As a second-year student, you would never have had such an opportunity in America.
Volunteer students usually pay for their own travel to Cameroon, often arriving with donated medicines.
But upon arrival in Yaoundé, their meals, transportation and training are paid for by Bvelle.
“He’s a hero, no doubt,” O’Malley said.
He gives his life to this organization, and his desire to help the people of Cameroon is endless.
For Bvelle, an almost constant workload is not a difficult test.
Helping others to live happily, keeping their father’s promise is what brings him great joy.
“I’m so happy when I do this job,” Bwelle said.
And I think about my father.
I hope he sees what I'm doing.
I do this to make people laugh, to relieve their pain.
Go to the ASCOVIME website and see how you can help.
