Agency "Rosbalt" deprived of the status of the media for obscene warfare
On October 31, the Moscow City Court decided to invalidate the license for the registration of the Rosbalt agency.
Roskomnadzor insisted on depriving the media agency of its status for systematic and gross violations of the law on media.
During the process, an unpleasant precedent was created: the court considered it possible to close the media, effectively refusing the publication the right to put forward counterarguments.
What is "Rosbalt"
CJSC Rosbalt News Agency was established in St. Petersburg in 2000.
In the following years, the agency opened a second head office in Moscow and a number of regional divisions.
The agency also has representative offices in the countries of the former USSR.
Since 2001, Rosbalt has been developing and functioning as a federal information and analytical agency.
By the mid-2000s, the agency was included in the list of the most recognizable private Internet media in Russia.
At the same time, Rosbalt has always occupied a rather specific niche: the core of the agency’s exclusive publications were (and still are) notes with reference to sources in law enforcement agencies.
Discussions about the proximity of the publication to the law enforcement agencies continued throughout the existence of the agency.
Along with the fact that "Rosbalt" had an extensive database of sources in various departments, in favor of such assumptions and said that the head of the project was Natalia Chaplina - wife of Viktor Cherkesov.
At the same time, Chaplin’s role in the leadership of Rosbalt is not completely clear: most often she is called the “project leader”.
The general director of the agency is Larisa Afonina, the editor-in-chief is Nikolay Ulyanov.
Recently, Rosbalt has not appeared in the ratings of the federal media - neither in terms of citations nor in terms of audience.
In October, the agency took the 25th place in the ranking of visits to Russian media sites according to LiveInternet.
According to the same LiveInternet, the average daily audience of the site rosbalt.ru is about 150 thousand unique visitors (and up to 500 thousand views), monthly - about three million unique visitors.
Among the most popular materials over the past five months are notes about the Kremlin’s helplessness in relations with Ukraine, the death of the soloist of the group “King and the Fool”, the pogroms in the capital Biryulev.
Rosbalt’s conflict with Roskomnadzor began in July 2013, when amendments to the law on the media came into force, forbidding journalists from obscene brawl.
The agency found banned vocabulary in two videos published on the agency's website ("Jigit from Krasnodar" and "Pussy Riot desecrated oil towers").
The other sides describe it differently.
Roskomnadzor on the basis of the discovered videos accused “Rosbalt” in a gross and systematic violation of the law on the media and appealed to the court with a request to withdraw the license from the agency.
Rosbalt claimed that the agency’s claims were unlawful: firstly, the videos were not editorial materials, secondly, the mother words in them were disguised, and thirdly, immediately after the warning, the videos were removed from the site.
Representatives of the agency appealed Roskomnadzor’s claims to the world court – and when on October 22, 2013, the Moscow City Court accepted Roskomnadzor’s claim, the consideration of these complaints was still ongoing.
However, already on the 25th, the world judge made a decision not in favor of Rosbalt: the editor-in-chief Nikolai Ulyanov was found guilty of violating the code of administrative offences and fined 20 thousand rubles - 10 thousand for each video.
Obviously, this predetermined the outcome of the hearing in the Moscow City Court - if we abandon the idea that the outcome could have been predetermined even earlier.
On October 31, the court decided to invalidate the certificate of registration of Rosbalt, effectively depriving the agency of the status of the media.
It cannot be said that Rosbalt was alone in this confrontation.
The Agency was supported by deputies of the State Duma (a statement addressed to the head of Roskomnadzor Alexander Zharov on October 10 was signed by 26 deputies; the document itself was filed at the initiative of the Communist Party).
The illegality of the closure of the publication was stated by the head of the Union of Journalists of Russia Vsevolod Bogdanov, the chairman of the Moscow Union of Journalists Pavel Gusev and the head of the Presidential Human Rights Council Mikhail Fedotov.
Moreover, according to Bogdanov, the leadership of Roskomnadzor even gave him some guarantees that the revocation of the license will not come.
The trial of “Rosbalt” showed: under whose jurisdiction it is safer to be a mass media in Russia today is a big question.
