Meanwhile, U.S. lawmakers will travel to Europe to help resolve issues related to alleged U.S. espionage abroad and convince Europeans to continue joint counterterrorism efforts with the U.S., the chairman of the Senate Subcommittee on European Affairs said on Thursday.
Connecticut Senator Chris Murphy said he spoke to members of the European Parliament and others this week and was concerned by their threats to end their involvement in anti-terrorism organizations due to frustration over surveillance by the National Security Agency.
“It is really important for U.S. national security interests that Europeans remain our supporters with regard to our common anti-terrorism efforts,” Murphy, a first-term Democrat who chairs the Senate’s international affairs subcommittee on European affairs, said in an interview from Washington.
“And I’m going to Europe to let them know that we must continue to cooperate in the fight against terrorism, despite their anger over these NSA programs.”
News that the NSA has collected millions of phone records in Europe has worsened relations with some U.S. allies, though the agency’s head said this week that they were inaccurate and reflected a misunderstanding of the metadata that NATO allies collected and shared with the U.S.
Other disclosures cited documents released by Snowden that showed that the NSA was monitoring the mobile phone of German Chancellor Angela Merkel, as well as the phones of about 34 other world leaders.
National Intelligence Director James Clapper defended allied espionage as necessary and said it was common practice on both sides.
Against the backdrop of this uproar, Murphy said his office is organising a trip by members of Congress that is expected to take place this year, and that he hopes the delegation will include members of both parties and both houses.
The names of the other legislators involved should be announced in the coming days.
According to him, the program of the trip is still under development.
While Murphy said the purpose of the trip was to promote better relationships, he said some degree of “best-intentioned hardness” would also be displayed.
He said European leaders should be honest with their people about what spyware they themselves have used for years.
“While we can change our surveillance programs to better protect the rights of Europeans, they also have to accept the fact that we are not the only ones doing intelligence,” Murphy said.
Meanwhile, Mr. Kerry is due to travel this weekend to the Middle East and Poland to address hostility to U.S. strategy in Syria, Egypt and Iran, as well as U.S. intelligence activities.
The influence of jailers will increase in the new compositions of public supervisory commissions
Today, the Council of the Public Chamber (OP) can approve new compositions of public monitoring commissions (ONC) in 43 regions of Russia.
If the option put to the vote is adopted, lobbyists of the security forces will increase their influence.
NPCs are public bodies that control the conditions of detention in places of detention.
The cases of Sergei Magnitsky and Leonid Razvozhaev, the unrest in the Kopek colony - it is through the ONC that most of the resonant incidents behind bars are publicized.
There is a struggle between human rights defenders and lobbyists of the security forces for control of the ONC.
At the meeting of the working group of the OP on the formation of the ONC, I proposed to make the experience of human rights activities a criterion for selection.
"He was not accepted, and formed lists without developing criteria," says Valery Borshchev.
Borshchev is the current chairman of the Moscow Monitoring Commission and the Association of Independent Observers, an all-Russian structure of human rights defenders dealing with prison issues.
When he was a deputy of the State Duma from Yabloko, he drafted a law regulating the activities of the ONC.
The OP Council must vote on the compositions of the ONC in 43 regions of the country.
Fewer than a thousand applicants are applying for 1,800 vacancies, and in Ingushetia and Kabardino-Balkaria competitions could not be organized due to the lack of candidates.
The OC promises to organize a re-recruitment for vacancies.
The ONC of Moscow is one of the few commissions with a competition, despite the fact that in the new composition instead of 20 there will be 40 participants.
According to Borshchev, in the current composition of the capital commission, 11 human rights defenders and 9 security forces, and in the version that is on the vote in the OP, the ratio changes by 17 to 23.
At the same time, 30 human rights defenders were wanted in the capital commission.
But the new composition can again enter the representative of the "Fighting Brotherhood" Vyacheslav Kalinin.
He had been a member of the ONC for three years, but had never visited prisoners.
Borshchev believes that the security forces, by appointing their chairman of the ONC, will be able to make the work of human rights defenders intolerable, so human rights defenders do not exclude collective withdrawal from the commission.
According to them, the promotion of the security forces is coordinated by the member of the ONC Anton Tsvetkov, who heads the "Officers of Russia" - an organization that defends the interests of law enforcement agencies.
"I don't eat babies on the trail," Anton Tsvetkov told RBC daily.
He denies lobbying for the promotion of any lists and says he has no intention of preventing human rights defenders from visiting arrested opposition figures.
According to Tsvetkov, he was not even interested in what list is currently being voted on in the OP.
Borschev’s disclosure of information he considers a form of pressure.
The possible success of human rights defenders is the planned change of the leadership of the Chelyabinsk ONC.
Its former executives will be suspended due to last year's cope uprisings.
The Public Chamber concluded that the leadership of the local commission ignored the problems of the prisoners.
But the ONC of Rostov-on-Don can move from human rights defenders to security forces.
The human rights defender-chairman of the local commission “disappeared” from the new lists, but one of his opponents turned out to be, despite the fact that in May 2013 the federal Public Chamber expelled him for unethical behavior.
Borshchev considers the lists of the Moscow and Rostov commissions to be “revenge for Kopeisk”.
The revelations of Nadezhda Tolokonnikova did not affect the ONC of Mordovia, which is considered a “force”: only one human rights activist wanted to get into the new composition, and she did not even accept documents for the competition.
Member of the OP Council Nikolai Svanidze told RBC daily that he voted against the proposed list, as he is outraged by the situation in Moscow and Rostov-on-Don.
He sent his position to the other members of the council.
His OP colleague Pavel Gusev says he voted in favour because he likes the proposed Moscow list.
The listing was coordinated by the Deputy Secretary of the OP Vladislav Grib, who is also an employee of the FSIN Research Institute.
Grib told RBC daily that he does not believe it is correct to divide the candidates for human rights defenders and security forces and does not agree that the chairmen of the commissions have enough powers to hinder the work of its members.
Mushroom is not taken to predict the results of the vote of the OP Council.
If the proposed list is rejected today, the amended version will be put to a vote in the coming days.
Australian Woman Appeals Against Imprisonment in Thailand
A 21-year-old Sydney woman sentenced to 15 days in prison on the island of Phuket for falsely claiming that she was attacked by a taxi driver, appealed the sentence and was released on bail.
Stevie Rochelle Bamford was initially found guilty on June 15 by the Phuket Provincial Court of filing a false lawsuit after Thai police reported that a local taxi driver carried out the attack on the night of Sunday, June 10, while two other men held her.
However, the CCTV footage later revealed that she returned safely to her hotel after breaking up with her Australian boyfriend.
Phuket police interrogated Bamford for two days before she admitted to fabricating the story.
Before the trial, she was held in local police cells.
Bamford was sentenced to a 15-day prison term in a general regime detention center on the outskirts of Phuket, rather than an adult women’s prison.
She is the daughter of former Australian League player Peter Tanks, who turned to the Foreign Office in Canberra for help for his daughter.
Tanks told the Sydney Sunday Telegraph that the entire family was “extremely concerned” about their daughter’s well-being and was waiting for her to return to Australia.
“Obviously, it was an alarming time, but we hope she will return home safely as soon as possible,” Tanks said.
Bamford appealed her sentence and was released on bail of 50,000 baht.
According to reports in Australia, she is currently spending her holidays in the resort area of Krabi in southern Thailand.
Thailand-based legal sources said Bamford is currently representing a local lawyer in Phuket, but warned that the appeal could lead to a court extending her sentence to two years and forcing her to serve time in an adult prison.
However, following the recent murder of Australian travel agent Michelle Smith in Phuket, Thailand may also seek to restore its undermined tourist image, leading to an acquittal.
